#step1 - remove everything that isn't a number, a slash, or an x|X
knoedler_dimensions_usd <- knoedler_usd %>%
  mutate(dims_cleaned = str_replace_all(dimensions, "\\[|\\]", "")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dimensions)) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = str_split(dims_cleaned, "x|X", simplify = TRUE)[,1],
         dim2 = str_split(dims_cleaned, "x|X", simplify = TRUE)[,2]) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = str_replace_all(dim1, "\\d/\\d", ""),
         dim2 = str_replace_all(dim2, "\\d/\\d", "")) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = str_replace_all(dim1, "[:alpha:]|[:punct:]", ""),
         dim2 = str_replace_all(dim2, "[:alpha:]|[:punct:]", "")) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = as.numeric(str_extract(dim1, "\\d\\d\\d|\\d\\d|\\d")),
         dim2 = as.numeric(str_extract(dim2, "\\d\\d\\d|\\d\\d|\\d"))) %>%
  mutate(inches_squared = dim1 * dim2)
knoedler_dimensions_usd <- knoedler_dimensions_usd %>%
  mutate(price_per_sqin = price_amount/inches_squared)

knoedler_dimensions_pounds <- knoedler_pounds %>%
  mutate(dims_cleaned = str_replace_all(dimensions, "\\[|\\]", "")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dimensions)) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = str_split(dims_cleaned, "x|X", simplify = TRUE)[,1],
         dim2 = str_split(dims_cleaned, "x|X", simplify = TRUE)[,2]) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = str_replace_all(dim1, "\\d/\\d", ""),
         dim2 = str_replace_all(dim2, "\\d/\\d", "")) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = str_replace_all(dim1, "[:alpha:]|[:punct:]", ""),
         dim2 = str_replace_all(dim2, "[:alpha:]|[:punct:]", "")) %>%
  mutate(dim1 = as.numeric(str_extract(dim1, "\\d\\d\\d|\\d\\d|\\d")),
         dim2 = as.numeric(str_extract(dim2, "\\d\\d\\d|\\d\\d|\\d"))) %>%
  mutate(inches_squared = dim1 * dim2)
knoedler_dimensions_pounds <- knoedler_dimensions_pounds %>%
  mutate(price_per_sqin = price_amount/inches_squared)

knoedler_dimensions_combined <- full_join(knoedler_dimensions_usd, knoedler_dimensions_pounds, by = c("dim1", "dim2", "inches_squared", "sale_date_year", "subject"))
View(knoedler_dimensions_combined)

golden_ratio_plot <- knoedler_dimensions_usd %>%
  mutate(ratio1 = dim1/dim2,
         ratio2 = dim2/dim1,
         bigratio = if_else(ratio1 >= ratio2, ratio1, ratio2),
         difference = abs(1.618 - bigratio)) %>%
  select(price_amount, difference) %>%
  filter(!is.na(price_amount)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = difference, y = price_amount)) +
  theme_classic() +
  geom_point(aes(color = difference)) +
  scale_color_continuous_sequential(palette = "ag_GrnYl") +
  scale_y_continuous(label = comma) +
  labs(title = "Golden Ratio Similarity versus Price",
       x = "Closeness to the Golden Ratio",
       y = "Price in USD",
       caption = "Smaller values are more golden") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

For the regression analysis of our data, weve begun with two primary models that reflect our research goals. Presently, we are using linear models - as our understanding of the data improves, we will use more appropriate types of GLMs that better reflect the non-linearity in the relationships between some of our variables.

The first model aims to predict the inflation-adjusted price of a painting by its primary physical attributes - country of origin, the subject & genre of the piece, and its size in square inches. As we expected, the predictive value of solely visual characteristics and sizes is quite limited - the R squared value of this model is .425, a value which indicates that approximately 42.5% of the variation in real prices is explained by linear relationships with our predictor variables. Although low for modelling purposes, 42.5% is quite high for a model that does not discriminate based on artist name. We expected all but the most famous paintings to have massively random pricing schemes, but the 42.5% figure suggests that general painting sales are less random than we might expect.

Interpreting the models coefficients begins with the nationality variable - the baseline dummy variable is American and thus each coefficient represents the difference between average paintings in a nationality and average American paintings. Unsurprisingly, the Dutch, Flemish, Bohemian, Greek & Spanish, Italian, and Russian coefficients are flagged as significant to at least the 1% level. All of these nationalities have positive coefficients and thus are more valuable on average than American works. However, Unknown nationality does not appear to be significant - one would expect that an unknown nationality would systematically lower its price, but the decrease observed in our data seems to be random noise.

sale_date_year is both statistically significant and has a positive coefficient of $2261 - a figure which suggests that each additional year leads to an average rise of $2261 in inflation-adjusted dollars. This figure is unsurprising -

The second model more directly addresses our variable of interest - price per square inch - and its relationship with the prior variables excluding raw size.

golden_all <- knoedler_dimensions_usd %>%
  mutate(ratio1 = dim1/dim2,
         ratio2 = dim2/dim1,
         bigratio = if_else(ratio1 >= ratio2, ratio1, ratio2),
         difference = abs(1.618 - bigratio)) %>%
  select(difference, price_amount) %>%
  filter(!is.na(difference), !is.na(price_amount))
golden_paintings <- golden_all %>%
  filter(difference <= .16) %>%
  select(price_amount)
nongolden_paintings <- golden_all %>%
  filter(difference > .16) %>%
  select(price_amount)

golden_means <- sample(golden_paintings$price_amount, size = c(10000, 1000), replace = TRUE)
nongolden_means <- sample(golden_paintings$price_amount, size = c(10000, 1000), replace = TRUE)
mean(golden_means>nongolden_means)
